body:
EDIT:

My mistake. This is normal behavior for potentially `Drop` types.

Original:

Possibly related to #105191. The compiler ignores `std::mem::drop` and thinks the drop occurs on the reassignment, `x = T::new_foo(buf);`:

```rust
trait Foo {
    type Output<'a>: Foo;
    fn new_foo<'a>(buf: &'a mut [u8]) -> Self::Output<'a>;
}

fn bar<T>(buf: &mut [u8])
where
    T: Foo,
{
    let mut x = T::new_foo(buf);
    loop {
        std::mem::drop(x);
        x = T::new_foo(buf);
    }
}
```

Removing the loop allows it to compile:

```rust
fn baz<T>(buf: &mut [u8])
where
    T: Foo,
{
    let mut x = T::new_foo(buf);
    std::mem::drop(x);
    x = T::new_foo(buf);

    // Reassigning a second time produces errors though
    // std::mem::drop(x);
    // x = T::new_foo(buf);
}
```

Compiler output where it completely misses the `std::mem::drop`:

```sh
error[E0499]: cannot borrow `*buf` as mutable more than once at a time
  --> src\main.rs:13:24
   |
10 |     let mut x = T::new_foo(buf);
   |                            --- first mutable borrow occurs here
...
13 |         x = T::new_foo(buf);
   |         -              ^^^ second mutable borrow occurs here
   |         |
   |         first borrow might be used here, when `x` is dropped and runs the destructor for type `<T as Foo>::Output<'_>`
```

### Meta
